Continuing since 8 November when first reported by Neil Palmer. Bird is moving around a lot but seems like it is figuring out where the food is and who has feeders out. First heard calling se of the Christian Ridge and 9th st fork.  Neil and I then walked up Christian Ridge road to Ange Heights to th the neighborhood off of Barney and Vancil st but didn’t find it. The resident right at the west side of the 9th/Christian Ridge fork had the bird show up her feeder right before we showed back up and within minutes we saw the bird again at the fork. The bird proceeded to come into the feed at 1387 9th street and proceeded south to every yard along 9th street until finally flying back up east towards the Vancil st neighborhood. Photos to be submitted to the CBRC. Nice to meet and bird with you, Neil!  Best suggestion is to hang out at the 9th/Christian Ridge fork as the bird will eventually come down to this neighborhood and seems to be getting into a pattern. And it’s super birdy in the area too.

Son handicap (mandibules déformées) nous permet de le repérer facilement et de suivre ses allées et venues. Il repart à chaque printemps pour nous revenir à l'automne. Sans en avoir la certitude, nous croyons qu'il s'agit de l'un de ces Geais bleu migrateur. Le Geai bleu est reconnu pour être un migrateur de courtes distances (quelques centaines de kilomètres). À l'automne, il quitterait les parties de son territoire qui sont situées plus au nord pour venir passer l'hiver avec nous dans le "Sud".

Observation Details: *large influx in what has been predicted to be a good fall for this species; northbound total represented here as a minimum estimate (540, clicked by 1s and 5s), plus a few lingering in the immediate area as I ended. Hard to make sense of what they were doing at first (partly because I was being overwhelmed by other things), but seems apparent now that they were overwhelmingly headed SW towards the point in the first few hours of the morning before swinging back north up the bay shore in typical fashion, although many birds simply remained around the point. Southbound total is likely undercounted given how busy I was in the first 90 minutes of the count, and certainly several hundred if not more still hanging out on Cape Island.

One of the Blue Jays slammed into our dining room window so hard that we thought it might have broken the glass.  It was a very warm summer day so the birds were already stressed from the heat.  This bird dropped to the grass where it stayed for several minutes, mouth open.  With my telephoto lens I was able to quietly observe it through the glass without adding to its stress.  After at least five minutes, it folded its wings and stayed still for another few minutes, finally flying off to join the other three birds that were visiting the feeders and the water bowl during the day.
